<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet>
    <title>Section 1.4 - Pivots and their influence on solution spaces</title>

    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Shown below are three augmented matrices in reduced row echelon
                form.
                For each matrix, identify the pivot positions and describe the
                solution space in <em>parametric form</em> (if any solutions
                exist).
            </p>
        </introduction>

        <task workspace="1in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr|r}
      1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </m>
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution component="05-solutions">
                <p>
                    <m>
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr|r}
      \textbf{\textcolor{blue}{1}} \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\
      0 \amp \textbf{\textcolor{blue}{1}} \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp \textbf{\textcolor{blue}{1}} \amp -2 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </m>
                </p>

                <p>
                    There are three pivots located in the 1st row and 1st
                    column, 2nd row and 2nd column, and 3rd row and 3rd column.
                    See bold blue entries above.
                    The solution in parametric form is <m>x_1 = 3</m>,
                    <m>x_2 = 0</m>, and <m>x_3 = -2</m>.
                    This means that there is one unique solution of
                    <m>{(x_1,x_2,x_3) = (3,0,-2)}</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr|r}
      1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </m>
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution component="05-solutions">
                <p>
                    <m>
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr|r}
      \textbf{\textcolor{blue}{1}} \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 3 \\
      0 \amp \textbf{\textcolor{blue}{1}} \amp -1 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </m>
                </p>

                <p>
                    There are two pivots located in the 1st row and 1st column
                    and 2nd row and 2nd column.
                    See bold blue entries above.
                    Reading from the matrix, we have the following system of
                    equations:
                    <md>
                        \ds
  \begin{alignedat}{4}
    x_1 \amp {}+{} \amp 2x_3 \amp  {}={}  \amp 3 \\
    x_2 \amp  {}-{} \amp x_3 \amp  {}={}  \amp 0 \\
  \end{alignedat}
                    </md>
                    where <m>x_3</m> is free since there is no pivot in the
                    column corresponding to that variable.
                    Writing these equations in parametric form we then have:
                    <m>{x_1 = -2x_3 + 3}</m> and <m>x_2 = x_3</m>.
                    Due to <m>x_3</m> being free, this system of equations has
                    infinitely many solutions.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr|r}
      1 \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </m>
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution component="05-solutions">
                <p>
                    <m>
  \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr|r}
      \textbf{\textcolor{blue}{1}} \amp 0 \amp 2 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp \textbf{\textcolor{blue}{1}} \amp -1 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \textbf{\textcolor{blue}{1}} \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
  </m>
                </p>

                <p>
                    There are three pivots located in the 1st row and 1st
                    column, 2nd row and 2nd column and 3rd row and 4th column.
                    See bold blue entries above.
                    This system has no solutions due to the third row, which has
                    a pivot in the rightmost column of the augmented matrix.
                    This third row yields the equation <m>0*x_3 = 1</m>, which
                    is not mathematically possible.
                    Therefore, there are no solutions.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise workspace=".5in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Each of these augmented matrices above has a row in which each
                entry is zero.
                What, if anything, does the presence of such a row tell us about
                the solution space to the linear system?
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution component="05-solutions">
            <p>
                Since all possibilities for the number of solutions (one, zero,
                or infinite) appear when there is a row of all zeros, we can't
                make any conclusions.
                When having a full row of zeros, one can only make conclusions
                about the number of solutions when the size of the matrix, the
                number of pivots, and the location of the pivots are known.
                For example, in Problem 1(a) above, every column of the
                coefficient matrix has a pivot, indicating one solution --
                therefore, the row of zeros has no impact on whether the system
                is consistent/inconsistent.
                For Problem 1(b) above, the row of zeros removes one of the
                pivots from the coefficient matrix, which introduces a free
                variable.
                Therefore, this row of zeros has an impact of creating an
                infinite solution set.
                We also see above in Problem 1(c) that there can be a row of all
                zeros and also a row that leads to an inconsistent system.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise workspace="1.5in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Give an example of a <m>3\times5</m> augmented matrix in reduced
                row echelon form that represents a consistent system.
                Indicate the pivot positions in your matrix and explain why
                these pivot positions guarantee a consistent system.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution component="05-solutions">
            <p>
                <md>
                    \left[
    \begin{array}{rrrr|r}
      \textbf{\textcolor{blue}{1}} \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\
      0 \amp \textbf{\textcolor{blue}{1}} \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 4\\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \textbf{\textcolor{blue}{1}} \amp 5 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                In this sample matrix, there is a pivot in every row of the
                coefficient matrix and there is no pivot in the rightmost column
                of the augmented matrix.
                Therefore, this system is consistent.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise workspace="1.5in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Give an example of a <m>3\times5</m> augmented matrix in reduced
                row echelon form that represents an inconsistent system.
                Indicate the pivot positions in your matrix and explain why
                these pivot positions guarantee an inconsistent system.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution component="05-solutions">
            <p>
                <md>
                    \left[
    \begin{array}{rrrr|r}
      \textbf{\textcolor{blue}{1}} \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp \textbf{\textcolor{blue}{1}} \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0\\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \textbf{\textcolor{blue}{1}} \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                In this sample matrix, there is a pivot the rightmost column of
                the augmented matrix.
                This represents an equation of <m>0 = 1</m>, or more
                specifically, <m>{0x_1+0x_2+0x_3+0x_4=1}</m>, which has no
                solutions (inconsistent).
            </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise workspace="1.1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                How do the pivot positions <term>in an augmented matrix</term>
                determine whether a linear system is consistent or not?
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution component="05-solutions">
            <p>
                If there is a pivot in the last column, then the system is
                inconsistent (no solutions).
                If there is no pivot in the last column, then the system is
                consistent (1 or infinitely many solutions).
            </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise workspace="1.5in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Suppose we have a linear system for which the
                <em>coefficient</em> matrix has the following reduced row
                echelon form.
                (The coefficient matrix is where we just don't write the last
                column of the augmented matrix, just the coefficients of the
                variables <m>{x_1,\dots, x_n}</m>.)
                <md>
                    \left[
    \begin{array}{rrrrr}
      1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
      0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2  \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0  \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -3 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
                </md>
                Even though we don't have any information about the right-hand
                side of the equations, what can you say about the consistency of
                the linear system?
                Explain your thinking.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution component="05-solutions">
            <p>
                <md>
                    \left[
    \begin{array}{rrrrr}
      \textbf{\textcolor{blue}{1}} \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
      0 \amp \textbf{\textcolor{blue}{1}} \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 2  \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp \textbf{\textcolor{blue}{1}} \amp 0 \amp 0  \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp \textbf{\textcolor{blue}{1}} \amp -3 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                This system is consistent regardless of the right hand side of
                the equation.
                This is because there is a pivot in every row (namely 1st row
                and column, 2nd row and column, 3rd row and column, and 4th row
                and column -- see bold blue entries above), which means that
                there aren't any more possible pivots for this system.
                Hence, there can't be a pivot in the augmented column.
                Therefore, by Problem 5, the system is consistent.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                The following augmented matrix is in reduced row echelon form.
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    \left[
    \begin{array}{rrrrr|r}
      1 \amp -2 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp 0 \amp 2 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 4 \\
      0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
                </md>
            </p>
        </introduction>

        <task workspace="1in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Describe the solution space in parametric form.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution component="05-solutions">
                <p>
                    The equations from the matrix are:
                    <md>
                        \ds
  \begin{alignedat}{4}
     x_1  {}-{} 2x_2 {}+{} 4x_4 \amp   {}={} \amp  2 \\
     x_3 {}+{} 3x_4 \amp  {}={} \amp -1 \\
     x_5 \amp   {}={} \amp  4 \\
  \end{alignedat}
                    </md>
                    This leads to the parametric form of:
                    <md>
                        \ds
  \begin{alignedat}{4}
    x_1 \amp {}={} 2x_2 - 4x_4 + 2 \\
    x_3 \amp {}={} -3x_4 - 1 \\
    x_5 \amp {}={} 4 \\
  \end{alignedat}
                    </md>
                    where <m>x_2, x_4</m> are free.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In the solution set a variable is called a
                    <em>free variable</em> if there is no restriction on that
                    value.
                    All other variables are called <em>basic variables</em>.
                    Identify the basic and free variables.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution component="05-solutions">
                <p>
                    The free variables are: <m>x_2, x_4</m>.
                </p>

                <p>
                    The basic variables are: <m>x_1, x_3, x_5</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>

        <task workspace="1in">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    What's the connection between pivot positions and basic/free
                    variables?
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution component="05-solutions">
                <p>
                    A variable is basic if the corresponding column has a pivot.
                    Otherwise, it is a free variable.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                If possible, give an example of a <m>3\times5</m> augmented
                matrix that corresponds to a system of linear equations having a
                unique solution.
                If it is not possible, explain why.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution component="05-solutions">
            <p>
                This is impossible since there can only be 3 pivot positions
                (since there are only 3 rows).
                However, a <m>3\times5</m> augmented matrix corresponds to
                having 4 variables.
                In order to have a unique solution, there much be a pivot in
                every column, with the number of pivots equalling the number of
                variables.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                If possible, give an example of a <m>5\times3</m> augmented
                matrix that corresponds to a system of linear equations having a
                unique solution.
                If it is not possible, explain why.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution component="05-solutions">
            <p>
                This is possible!
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    \left[
    \begin{array}{rr|r}
      1 \amp  0 \amp 2 \\
      0 \amp  1 \amp 3 \\
      0 \amp  0 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp  0 \amp 0 \\
      0 \amp  0 \amp 0 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                This yields the unique solution <m>{(x_1,x_2) = (2,3)}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                What condition on the pivot positions guarantees that a system
                of linear equations has a unique solution?
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution component="05-solutions">
            <p>
                If there is a pivot position in every column corresponding to a
                variable (this does not include the last column of an augmented
                matrix), there is a unique solution.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                If a system of linear equations has a unique solution, what can
                we say about the relationship between the number of equations
                and the number of unknowns?
                Use the concept of pivot positions to explain your thinking.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution component="05-solutions">
            <p>
                There must be at least as many rows as columns in the
                coefficient matrix because this will allow for a pivot position
                in every column.
                Therefore, it must be that the number of equations is greater
                than or equal to the number of variables.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                For what values of the parameter <m>k</m> is the following
                system consistent?
                For which of those values is the solution unique?
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    \ds
  \begin{alignedat}{4}
    -x_1 {}+{} 2x_2 \amp {}={} \amp  3 \\
    2x_1 {}-{} 4x_2 \amp  {}={} \amp k \\
  \end{alignedat}
                </md>
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution component="05-solutions">
            <p>
                First, we use Gaussian elimination to get the matrix in row
                reduced echelon form:
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>
                    \left[
    \begin{array}{rr|r}
      -1 \amp  2 \amp 3 \\
      2 \amp  -4 \amp k \\
    \end{array}
  \right] \amp \xrightarrow{(-1*R1) \rightarrow R1} \amp \left[
    \begin{array}{rr|r}
      1 \amp  -2 \amp -3 \\
      2 \amp  -4 \amp k \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
                </mrow>
                    <mrow>
                    \amp \xrightarrow{(R2 - 2*R1) \rightarrow R2} \amp \left[
    \begin{array}{rr|r}
      1 \amp  -2 \amp -3 \\
      0 \amp  0 \amp k+6 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
                </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                In order to have a consistent system, there can be no pivot in
                the rightmost column.
                Therefore, this system is consistent when
                <m>k+6 = 0 \Rightarrow k = -6</m>.
                There will never be a unique solution because there is no pivot
                in the second column.
                As long as <m>k = -6</m>, there are infinitely many solutions.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise workspace="1in">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Say we have <m>(1,12)</m>, <m>(2,9)</m>, and <m>(3,5)</m>.
                Find a polynomial of degree 2 of the form
                <md>
                    f(x) = ax^2 + bx + c
                </md>
                whose graph passes through these points.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution component="05-solutions">
            <p>
                For all of the given points <m>(x,y)</m>, we want it to be true
                that <m>f(x) = y</m>.
                However, we also have that <m>{f(x) = ax^2 + bx + c}</m>.
                Combining these elements, we have the following system of
                equations:
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    \ds
  \begin{alignedat}{4}
    12 \amp {}={} \amp f(1) \amp {}={} \amp a*1 {}+{} b*1 {}+{} c  \\
    9 \amp {}={} \amp f(2) \amp {}={} \amp a*4 {}+{} b*2 {}+{} c  \\
    5 \amp {}={} \amp f(3) \amp {}={} \amp a*9 {}+{} b*3 {}+{} c  \\
  \end{alignedat}
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                We then have the corresponding augmented matrix, on which we can
                perform Gaussian Elimination to find the solution:
            </p>

            <p>
                <md>
                    \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr|r}
      1 \amp  1 \amp 1 \amp 12 \\
      4 \amp  2 \amp 1 \amp 9 \\
      9 \amp  3 \amp 1 \amp 6 \\
    \end{array}
  \right] \sim \left[
    \begin{array}{rrr|r}
      1 \amp  0 \amp 0 \amp -1/2 \\
      0 \amp  1 \amp 0 \amp -3/2\\
      0 \amp  0 \amp 1 \amp 14 \\
    \end{array}
  \right]
                </md>
            </p>

            <p>
                This yields a unique solution of
                <m>(a,b,c) = (-1/2, -3/2, 14)</m>, giving the degree two
                polynomial of <m>f(x) = \frac{-1}{2}x^2 - \frac{3}{2}x + 14</m>.
            </p>
            <sage>
                <input>
A = matrix(3,4,[1,1,1,12,
                4,2,1,9,
                9,3,1,5])
A.rref()
                </input>
                <output>
[1 0 0 -1/2]
[0 1 0 -3/2]
[0 0 1 14]
                </output>
            </sage>

            <image>
                <shortdescription>
                    Graph of <m>f(x) = \frac{-1}{2}x^2 - \frac{3}{2}x + 14</m>
                    going through the 3 given points.
                </shortdescription>
                <prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="05-1-4_1">
                    <diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                        <definition>
                            f(x)=-x^2/2-3*x/2+14
                        </definition>

                        <definition>
                            a = 1
                        </definition>
                        <coordinates bbox="(-15,-15,15,20)">
                            <grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="f(x)"/>
                            <graph function="f"/>
                            <point p="(1,12)" alignment="ne" fill="orange">
                                <m>
                                    (1,12)
                                </m>
                            </point>
                            <point p="(2,9)" alignment="ne" fill="orange">
                                <m>
                                    (2,9)
                                </m>
                            </point>
                            <point p="(3,5)" alignment="ne" fill="orange">
                                <m>
                                    (3,5)
                                </m>
                            </point>
                        </coordinates>
                    </diagram>
                </prefigure>
            </image>
        </solution>
    </exercise>

    <outcomes>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Make sure you can answer the following questions:
            </p>
        </introduction>

        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    What's a free variable?
                    What's a basic variable?
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    What is a pivot position?
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    What is a consistent system?
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    How can you tell that a linear system is inconsistent using
                    the pivot positions of the corresponding augmented matrix?
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    How can you tell a linear system has infinitely many
                    solutions based on the pivot positions of the corresponding
                    coefficient matrix?
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </outcomes>
</worksheet>